Vaccination against pneumococcal diseases will be free and optional
Vaccination against the pneumococcal reversed the old habits as early as January.
It will be the first to be free and at the same time optional for families.
Critics already, saying that a compulsory vaccination would be more effective.
The preparations for the introduction of the free vaccination against pneumococcal.
The pharmaceutical institute for vaccines already defines the maximum prices that will pay for health insurance.
The experts are also clear in the process of vaccination.
A new vaccination.
Free vaccines for children of August.
Since January, children born last year from 2 August can be vaccinated against pneumococcal free.
The condition is that they have not yet been vaccinated.
If we started vaccination last year or earlier, we will have to pay yourself following vaccinations.
The first dose of vaccine should be administered between the third and the fifth month of the child.
Last year a quarter of families has voluntarily vaccinated children against pneumococcal.
Yet parents paid 1,600 crowns or more for a dose.
The vaccination of younger requires four doses.
Experts estimate that each year the health insurance spend 300 to 450 million kronor in doses of vaccine.
However, they save on medical care that unvaccinated children require.
So far the state spends about 500,000 crowns per year for the vaccination of children.
The vaccination repaid was introduced with the "package Janota."
The pneumococcal are the cause of inflammation of the middle ear but also serious infections including inflammation of the brain and blood poisoning.
According to surveys in hospitals, until 28 deaths of children under 10 years caused by pneumococcal infections.
Apart from the Czech Republic, about 40 other countries have introduced vaccination repaid.
The vaccination will be mandatory?
There are opinions regarding a possible mandatory vaccination in the future.
From January, it must be resolved by insurance and optional.
For example, the president of the association Nahlas Rudolf Kalovský indicated that a compulsory vaccination would be more positive.
His association has long promoted vaccination against pneumococcal bacteria.
At an international conference in which our association participated, experts were not really satisfied with the fact that we have a voluntary vaccination.
This is not ideal.
On the other hand, we are pleased to have been able to impose at least this.
I think it is a direction that it must now follow said Kalovský.
But the ministry of health does not change the process of vaccination against pneumococcus.
We are absolutely not for the moment, "said his spokesman Vlastimil sršeň.
The voluntary vaccination has its drawbacks, say doctors.
Hana Cabrnochová, president of the Society of paediatricians, acknowledged that a vaccine based on the Volontariata its shortcomings.
If all children were vaccinated, it could consider a reduction of renewals of vaccinations "In the situation where the vaccine is such a sum I understand the decision making vaccination optional" said however Cabrnochová.
The experts predict that next year, more than 80 per cent of new parents will vaccinate their infants.
Vaccination against pneumococcal bacteria marks a break from the fact that this is the first vaccination of children that is funded by the insurance and not the state.
Cabrnochová explained that insurance should free up funds for prevention, they would save and on possible future medical care.
Doctors will have to buy their products themselves.
This is linked to the concerns of paediatricians practitioners, which relate to the purchase of vaccines.
The original intent was to purchase vaccines by insurance, doctors the receiving the same way as other products of vaccine provided by the state.
Some Members were concerned, however, that this would allow insurance companies to deduct the amount of health insurance. "
Thus, doctors will have to buy the products and wait for insurance them back.
According to estimates, pediatricians will individually invest nearly 40 000 sek per month in vaccines, which is a significant sum.
It will be far from easy, according to Cabrnochová.
