The Marines, among the 6,000 people who have laid wreaths on the graves in Arlington
The first class Angello robinson, 19, made a trip of seven hours by bus to file a simple wreath on the grave of a soldier that he had never met.
For him and the other Marine who made the trip to Camp Johnson in Jacksonville, North Carolina at Arlington National Cemetery to decorate the graves, this day was devoted to salute the men and women who, one day, were in their place.
In a few months, where we will be sent, we will be in their place, said Robinson about the fallen soldiers.
If it was me, I would like someone to do the same thing for me, that is why I just trying to show respect.
It was one of the 6,000 volunteers to be gathered Saturday morning to lay wreaths on the graves of veterans, in different sections of the cemetery of Arlington Ceremony.
In 1992, Morrill Worcester, owner of Worcester Wreath Company to Harrington, in Maine, launched the commemoration and others have decided to decorate hundreds of graves in the cemetery of Arlington Ceremony.
Now, to continue a tradition of 18 years, Morrill and his wife karen, each year the trip, stopping in different cities on their way to organize the commemorations in honour of the military and victims of terrorism.
The Worcester have also founded a non-profit association, Wreaths Across America (of Wreaths Across America), which aims to promote the event in all other states.
This year, volunteers have placed more than 16,000 wreaths on the graves of the Cemetery of Arlington, around the pentagon, on the graves of the Cemetery Fayetteville National Cemetery enarkansas_OOV, in Battery Park in New York City and on the site of the memorial to the victims of United Airlines Flight 93 in shanksville, pennsylvania.
For the second consecutive year, the Walmart Foundation has given more than $150,000 to buy and transport the crowns.
Charleen hunt, 70, of westminster, said that she had made the trip to Arlington in honour of her husband, a career soldier died.
Although her husband is not buried at arlington, Hunt said that for her, it was a way to thank those who had sacrificed.
It is a small gesture that can make the civilians to support our troops, she said.
It is like visiting a family tomb.
All in several layers of warm clothing, volunteers walked between the lawns and hills tracts of the cemetery.
The volunteers have chosen ancient tombs, dating from the First and Second World War, and the Vietnam War, because they are not as often visited the new graves, said the organizers.
The mood was optimistic, while children played and couples were held by the hand, wearing the crowns of fresh pine on the graves.
Each round crown had a dark green colour, with a small red butterfly knot on the top.
Nearby, were silent on Section 60, where most of the veterans of the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan are buried.
The United Service Organizations gave 1,000 crowns to decorate the section but the sour mood of the current wars filled the area.
People wept openly, others prayed and families and friends supported in the cold air.
Some read aloud the names engraved in stone while others have commented to see small black and white information cards, stuck in the wetland for those whose tomb had not yet been completed.
Sandra Lockwood was one of the many mothers in tears, on the grave of his son.
It is part of Zanesfield, in Ohio and had led eight hours to come to gather at the tomb of Marine Sergeant GunneryDavid Shane Spicer, who died in combat in July.
No one should never forget thanks to what we are free … my son has paid for it, she said.
"long after I have disappeared, I want someone to remember him."
A US citizen arrested by the Cuban authorities
The Cuban government has arrested an American citizen who was distributing mobile phones and laptop computers in the country, said the services of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs.
The citizen, which has not yet been identified, works for Development Alternatives Inc., based in Bethesda.
The company is working on projects for clients such as the U.S. Agency for International Development and the World Bank.
The consular authorities as well as the U.S. Interest Section in Havana trying to gain access to the inmate who was arrested on 5 December.
The specific charges have not been made public, although under the Cuban law, a Cuban citizen or a foreign visitor may be arrested under the pretext of "dangerous".
All the so-called revolutionary activities, including protests moderate and critical writing, the risk of arrest.
The graffiti and speeches are regarded as serious crimes.
Cuba has a community of bloggers, conducted by Yoani Sánchez, popular commentator who writes often about how she and her husband are followed and harassed by Government agents.
Sánchez has made several requests to leave the country to receive rewards but authorities have always been denied.
The detention of an American citizen may increase tensions between the communist government of brothers in Cuba and the Obama administration which pursues a "soft" approach to improve relations with the island.
The announcement of the arrest was first reported by the New York Times, Friday evening.
The new American policy insists that the Cuban government advance by concrete steps, such as freeing political prisoners and create more space for the opposition, so that the US to reciprocate.
Mobile phones and laptops are allowed to Cuba, although new consumer goods and desired in a country or the average salary of an employee is $15 per month.
Only this year, the Cuban government has granted to ordinary citizens the right to buy mobile phones; they are mainly used for text messages or for a 15-minute conversation which corresponds to a day of salary.
On the island, the use of the Internet is extremely limited.
It is available in luxury hotels and for foreign visitors in the country, as well as in some government buildings, such as universities.
The Cubans who want to connect often must provide their name to the government.
Access to many Web sites is restricted.
The detention of an American in Cuba is rare.
Most of the few US in Cuba are behind bars for crimes such as drug trafficking, "says Gloria Berbena, press officer of from the U.S. Interests Section in Havana.
Berbena said that she could not provide more information on the arrest.
The arrest and detention are a big mistake.
An activity which, in any other open society, would be authorized -- distribute free mobile phones -- is a crime in Cuba, "said Jose Miguel Vivanco, Americas Program Director of the group Human Rights Watch, which recently published a harsh report on freedoms in Cuba, called" new Castro, Cuba ", referring to the installation of Raul Castro as the leader of the country to replace Fidel, his older brother ill.
According to Vivanco, a defendant is often arrested, tried and imprisoned on the same day.
He said that any solution would probably be political and that the Cuban government often causes a negative reaction in the United States, when the two countries are beginning to initiate a dialogue.
The Pakistani authorities prevented a plot to send men in Afghanistan
Saturday, the Pakistani authorities have identified an alleged organizing a conspiracy to send five men of Northern Virginia in Afghanistan in order to kill American troops, saying that they hoped that this case would help to dismantle a large network of recruiters of terrorists scouring the Internet looking for young men radicalized.
Investigators have said that they were hunting a personality Insurgente hidden, known as Saifullah which invited these men in Pakistan after having discovered when one of them made comments endorsing the terrorist waves on the video site YouTube on the Internet.
Arriving in Pakistan, these men have been guided by Saifullah who tried to help them reach the remote area of the tribal belt of Pakistan, home of al-Qaida and its terrorist training camps.
But a representative of the Pakistani secret services which had been informed of the case said Saturday that Saifullah had failed to convince the Al-Qaeda commanders that these men were not involved in the conspiracy of the CIA to infiltrate the terrorist network.
As a result, they have been isolated for days in the eastern city of Sargodha, far from the mountains of northeastern become a shelter of terrorism.
They have been as undercover agents.
That is why they were rejected, said a representative of the authorities who spoke on condition of anonymity because of the confidential nature of the case.
The representative of the authorities said that men were determined and they are still trying to obtain the necessary permissions for entry into the camps of al-Qaeda when they were arrested by the forces of Pakistani law.
The case of these five men -- who remain in Pakistan and who are interviewed by the FBI -- insist on the crucial role of recruiters in the identification of potential terrorists and perhaps more important, in the determination of people who trust.
Since the attacks of 11 September 2001, the US secret services have been a priority for infiltrate men in the al-Qaeda network.
The organization recruiters play the role of firewalls, refusing entry to those who do not show a serious commitment and those who can prove to be spies.
According to analysts, the potential American recruits are studied closely by al-Qaeda.
But they are also very attractive to the group because of their potential access to American targets and propagandaire of their value.
However Evan Kohlmann, expert of the Foundation based in the United States, said that the terrorist groups must also do more and more attention in recent years in the choice of the people they accept as the US secret services have become experts in their recruitment methods.
If you try to infiltrate someone in these groups, what better way than to follow its recruitment model that so many other people have already followed? said Kohlmann.
The model is increasingly on the Internet.
