Many are also those whose parents set high goals for their children and find ways to compensate for their lack of familiarity with American schools.
The mentoring programs also play a very important role in helping Graciela and millions of children as it to reach the university -- in particular, if its efforts are regular and long-term.
When you look at the children of low-income families with parents who do not have the experience and skills to help them navigate the system, any intervention, at any time, will not help, said Patricia Gándara, researcher at University of California, Davis, who has studied Latin American students.
We need to provide a support network for these children, from kindergarten to high school.
The federal program which funded the visit of universities of Graciela is a good example.
Known as the GEAR UP (you), it provides more than $300 million a year to local school systems to organize programmes of preparation for the university which began when students from low income families are in middle school (College) and continue until the end of years of high school.
Since 1999, the programme has been followed by more than 10 million students, with more than 60 percent entering the university, according to the US Department of education.
The Ministry of Iraqi oil has agreements with 10 foreign oil companies
Despite the concerns about violence and political instability, the Iraqi government has managed to attract major oil companies to rebuild its infrastructure in difficulty during two auction that ended Saturday.
The 10 agreements reached by the Iraqi Ministry of Oil with the foreign Oil companies suggest that Oil companies from china, Russia and Europe are poised to play a major role in the rehabilitation of the Oil industry of iraq, invalidated by decades of war and sanctions.
American companies are left with an interest in only two of 10 fields auctioned.
Seven US companies had paid to participate in the second auction that began Friday.
The only one that had set an auction has lost.
Two American companies have obtained contracts for the fields auctioned in June.
The low representation of American oil giants in the opening of the oil sector in Iraq has surprised analysts.
Iraq has finally opened its doors, after six years of war, and instead of American companies, are of Asian and European companies that pave the way, "said Ruba husari, editor of the forum Iraq Oil forum, a site of information on the internet.
It will take a long time before another offer is made in Iraq.
The concerns about security, corroborated by massive bombings coordinated, tuesday, and the political instability that american troops withdraw have slowed the american oil companies, preventing them from entering with more force in iraq, which has the third largest crude oil reserve in the world, say analysts.
The American companies were, in some cases, disadvantaged because of their rivals, especially the Chinese and other energy companies controlled by a government, whose labour costs were significantly lower and who were more willing to take risks because they had not accountable to shareholders.
Exxon-Mobil and Occidental Petroleum Inc. were the only American companies to obtain contracts with the department.
The most important American companies, such as Chevron and ConocoPhillips, which have maintained strong ties with the Iraqi Oil Ministry and brought their technical advice, came away empty-handed.
The Russian companies Lukoil and Gazprom were the two main shareholders in two of the contracts awarded this weekend.
The Chinese National Petroleum Corp., owned by the state, has more on contracts that other companies and is left with significant holdings in contracts for two major fields.
We all know that China is becoming a major economy, as well as a technological power, "said Assam Jihad, spokesman of the Ministry of Oil.
We are confident that the Chinese company will be equal to its competitors and achieve its commitments in Iraq.
Pre-selected companies to submit auctions have made offers that were then compared to the rate per barrel that the department agreed to pay to motivate the production above current levels for each field.
