Saleh al-Somali was one of two Arab men suspected to have been killed by a pair of missiles launched in their car, Tuesday, near the town of Miran shah, in the province of North waziristan, according to us sources and Pakistani authorities in the region.
Local authorities have said that the missiles had been fired by a pilotless aircraft of the type used by the CIA, inside the lawless tribal border of Pakistan.
They were driving a white car, heading towards the Afghan border, when the car was struck, said a member of the secret services Pakistani civilians, speaking by telephone of Miran shah.
The representatives of the authority have said that local activists suspects rushed to place and quickly confiscated what remained of "body completely shredded".
It was completely impossible for local authorities to verify the identity of the victims, but the two American counterterrorism officials provided unspecified evidence that Somali was part of the dead.
Somali was described as one of the organisers, military officials who ran Al Qaeda terrorist operations of the group out of the Afghanistan-Pakistan region.
Its role was to organize conspiracies in the world, "said one of the authorities who wished to remain anonymous, citing the sensitive nature of air strikes inside Pakistani territory.
Given its central role, this probably included conspiracies of attacks against the United States and Europe.
It followed the instructions strategic leaders of al-Qaeda and has translated into action plans for possible terrorist attacks.
A second representative of the American authority said that Somali had increased rapidly in the ranks of al-Qaida' s and had very good relations with other extremist groups in the region.
It may not be known to the general public, but this does not diminish the threat it poses for us and our allies, said the second official representative.
