A panel of Roman sarcophagus that belonged to the French writer Emile Zola was awarded Thursday $1.5 million, well above its estimate, announced the art dealer Sotheby's.
This sign before two metres long on 63 cm high, dating from the third century a.d., was estimated between $150,000 and $250,000.
The marble "representing four other scenes in a sophisticated architectural decoration, surrounded by satyres and bacchantes, is a rare piece, there are only four or five in the world," explained to AFP Tuesday Florent Heintz, vice-president of the auction of art of the Roman and Egyptian antiquities in Sotheby's.
It was sold among 100 lots.
The sale is still ongoing but this lot is certainly the one on which buyers have the most excellent so far, has indicated to AFP spokesperson for Sotheby's, Dan Abernethy.
The discovery of the acquisition of the marble by Emile Zola back to a few days.
The sign remained nearly 300 years in Rome in the famous collection of the Borghese family, then became successively among French actress Cécile Sorel, who had been an element of his bathtub in his mansion in Paris, and Paul Reynaud, Minister under the Third Republic in France and briefly chairman of the Council before the accession to power of Marshal Pétain.
Remained a grey area of 50 years.
