After three sessions of marathon talks, the road sector unions and employers' organisation TLF, only to be stayed until the end, arrived Friday evening at an agreement that puts an end to the strike and the threat to supplies of Christmas.
At the meeting of signatures Friday evening, the secretary of state for transport, Dominique Bussereau, was "pleased" of the agreement, after several rounds of negotiations, which began Wednesday morning.
After a second night of discussions the negotiators were left in the early morning friday, with the hope of sign quickly in late morning the text of the agreement.
And even if three employers' organisations (FNTR, Unostra, OTRE) had slammed the door.
But it took more than six hours of a meeting began at 11 a.m. so that everyone to agree and 00 the text is signed.
The conflict "would have been very damaging for business" and "it was feared that he disrupt the christmas and new years," said Mr bussereau.
The text provides for a pay increase of 4% for the lowest wages (in the local and regional road transport), and 2.9% for the highest (international).
In hourly rate, for, "from 8.72 euros to 9.06.
It is not much, but it is very far, said Patrice closed (FO).
This is going to give the order to our activists that there is no, no amount of supplies.
But we can always have a few holdouts who are not happy, he added.
Philippe Grillot, president of TLF, welcomed "a good agreement", even if it was "difficult to concede the increases on the senior salaries because of international competition."
According to him, the increases will be of the order of EUR 170 monthly for low wages and 100 to 120 euros for the highest.
It is the agreement of common sense and the respect of employees, "said Maxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) has welcomed" a historic agreement ".
Richard Jaubert (cgt) has raised "an acceptable compromise.
The agreement also provides for the upgrading of travel expenses of 3%, and the holding of general state of road transport in the first half of 2010, which will address the issue of a 13th month and modernization of the collective agreement.
Mr Bussereau reiterated that "a decrease of EUR 100 million in employers' has been the subject of a Government amendment to draft amending finance law for 2009, voted in the night from Thursday to Friday by the National Assembly.
The government will ask the Senate to vote "in the same."
The signing of TLF allows the Agreement applies initially to the member companies to this organization, and in a second time, the entire profession, in case of an extension by the Minister of Labour.
It will be "as soon as possible," Mr bussereau.
The opposition of employers' organisations can only delay the process.
The FNTR denounced a "fool", because the eur 100 million "had already been promised the sector to offset a portion of the carbon tax".
The Secretary of state for transport has obliged us to negotiate in the emergency, not the conclusion of a shared analysis, but not to thwart turkey eaters the next eve, deplored the unostra_OOV.
For the school, the agreement risk "digging the grave of a very large number of SMEs in the sector in the next 12 months".
