The Turkish Justice dissolved the pro-Kurdish party, decision fraught with consequences
The Turkish Constitutional Court said Friday the dissolution of the main pro-Kurdish party in the country, a decision that was immediately followed by demonstrations of anger in the Kurdish community, in the south-east of the country and in istanbul.
This decision could greatly complicate the task of the government, which is to reach out to the Kurdish community to try to end 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society Party (dtp) was dissolved because it had become a "home of activities detrimental to the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," said to the press the president of the court Hasim kiliç, after four days of deliberations.
The decision was made unanimously of the 11 judges, while a qualified majority of seven votes was required to deliver the dissolution, said Mr kiliç, adding that 37 of party officials, including its president Ahmet türk and member armenia tugluk_OOV, are banned from politics for five years.
The judge also announced the lifting of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr. Türk and Mrs Tugluk and the confiscation of the property of the party.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (550).
Its leaders had warned before the verdict that Members would leave Parliament rather than sit as Members without labels.
The decision follows a process launched in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Court of Cassation Abdurrahman yalçinkaya, who accuses the DTP to obey the "directives" of the Kurdistan Workers Party (pkk), considered a terrorist organisation by Ankara and many countries.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political showcase of PKK rebels.
The party, however, that there was "no organic links" with the PKK but refuses to call it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with him.
The verdict of the Court comes as the government has to reach out to the Kurdish community in proposing a series of measures strengthening its rights, to try to shrink the support of Kurds in the PKK and put an end to the conflict.
The leaders of the DTP had said dissolution could lead to a resurgence of tensions in the south-east anatolia, where many demonstrations against the conditions of detention of the PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan degenerated into clashes with the police in recent weeks.
Since the announcement of justice, a thousand demonstrators gathered in front of the DTP in Diyarbakir, the largest city in the southeast populated mainly by Kurds.
The security forces fired tear gas and used water cannons, while protesters throwing Molotov cocktails and stones, with slingshots.
About 100 people demonstrated in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Mr Türk said that the decision of Justice would "deepen despair."
Turkey cannot solve this issue (Kurdish, Ed) by banning a party, he said to the press.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also deplored the decision.
We are opposed in principle to the closure of the parties.
This resolves nothing, "said Minister of Energy Taner yildiz.
This decision is a sinking total of democratic openness launched by the government, commented on the political analyst Ahmet insel.
We can expect, of course, a reaction from the PKK, he added.
Thursday, the PKK has claimed an attack that had killed seven soldiers three days earlier in the north of Turkey, one of the most deadly in recent months.
The new "silicon valley"
For a long time she had the reputation of city secret, off-limits to visitors.
Zelenograd, one of the 10 districts of Moscow, was under the Soviet regime, a place of secret weapons, under strict supervision.
Today, with its 216 000 inhabitants to 37 km from the centre of Moscow, the municipality has the reputation of being the "Silicon Valley" Soviet.
Important production sites and research into micro and Nanoelectronics are located.
As early as September 2008 representatives of Zelenograd have established links with Riedberg, place des Sciences Mehr – with academic institutions and companies of the centre of innovations in Frankfurt (FIZ).
There have been meetings and last Wednesday representatives of Zelenograd and Riedberg have ratified a "protocol of close collaboration".
The signatories were the deputy mayor of Moscow Juri Rosljak and the prefect Anatoly Smimov of Zelenograd for the Russian delegation, Edwin Schwartz head of section project for Frankfurt.
In 2010, representatives of the FIZ and SMEs, whose strong point is scientific research, will depart at Zelenograd for a seminar.
Scientific Exchange
It is a scientific exchange.
But also of economic relations.
It will enable the companies to enter the Russian market in full expansion.
Unlike the Russian scientific societies wish to obtain contracts in Germany.
Zelenograd is the headquarters of research institutes and companies Soviet famous.
There is the Institute of Electrical Engineering from Moscow, the major firms Sitronics and Rosssijskaja-Elektronika.
The joint was founded in 1958 as "socialist planned city" for research.
Zelenograd (literal translation "Green City") gets its name from the wooded hills in the heart of which research centres are located.
The project S21: a brake for Stuttgart
We cannot place high enough the magnitude of the Stuttgart 21 project.
To its supporters it is nothing less than "new heart of Europe".
If you want. S21, it is more that the burial of a railway station, more than a colossal construction project that will plunge the heart of the capital of baden-württemberg, in a chaos despairing yards for a decade.
Stuttgart 21 is born of the spirit of the 1980s.
The stations head of line, with lines that ended in town, had a reputation at the time of the relics of the technique of transport in the 19th century which were effect of brake shoe modern rail traffic as it once needed a lot of time to get the locomotives from front to rear.
Arrival, stopping short, departure – that is to do.
That is why the stations front line must disappear: in Frankfurt and munich.
And Stuttgart also: a station of trains, which is about halfway on the major trans-European rail between Paris and Budapest / Bratislava where the slogan "heart of Europe".
The project S21 will really start, although the visions of the 1980s are no longer compatible with reality.
Even the most ambitious planners have recognized that the cost to bury the station in the capitals of Hesse and Bavaria, was exorbitant.
In fact, the head of the line no longer pose real problems of entry and exit since there are modern trains, reversible with and Voiture-pilote at both ends.
It is now the achievement of Stuttgart 21 alongside the new route of the inter-city line towards Ulm.
The regional and communal prevailed.
The railway company is in part because it is the taxpayer who paid the cost of the largest infrastructure project of the federal republic and not the public company.
From the point of view this project is relatively well justified.
You get an urban space that – if it believes the computer-generated graphics planners – will be very green.
For the system of rail transport the S21 is harmful.
The station and the enlargement of the section are designed for traffic to which we assigned - and this is typical of the 1980s - a huge growth.
At the time there was no competition from cheap flights.
The policy of modern traffic should first concentrate on strengthening the traffic of goods as transport by rail is much more environmentally friendly by truck on the road.
But the new route, with its inclinations, not suitable for freight trains.
The s21, and this is much more serious indirectly affects many other rail projects.
For example, six billion euros will be swallowed up in the Swabian.
It is the official figure.
Experts believe that ten to fifteen billion are more realistic.
One thing is for sure, in the next decade this money will other junctions and congestion in the network.
The list of the Department of Transportation says 60 major projects.
One of the most important is the enlargement of the section across the Rhine Valley 180 miles.
Since 1987 this line is built in slow motion.
It would be really urgent support here to build on the fungus.
But the project is a braking.
The route of the Rhine Valley is becoming the bottleneck international freight traffic, and this in the heart of Europe.
