The case Kunduz
Frontal attack of the opposition: the head of the parliamentary group of the Greens, Jürgen Trittin, accused the Minister of Defence of lying in the Case of Kunduz.
The SPD party and The Left Party (Die Linke) asked Chancellor explanations.
Hamburg / Berlin - After examining the latest information on the air attack of Kunduz, the opposition has criticized the Defense Minister Karl-Theodor zu Guttenberg (CSU) to have délibérémentdissimulé some facts.
The Minister has intentionally "made an untruth" on the deadly strike two tankers last September, said the head of the parliamentary group of the Greens, Jürgen Trittin, Saturday during the broadcast of information of the chain ARD "Tagesschau" (the newspaper pm).
This means that he lied.
The order to kill was given in total disregard of the rules of the International Security Assistance Force in Afghanistan (ISAF).
It is, in essence, the content of the report available to NATO and which was read by Mr Guttenberg, said Trittin.
Last Friday, according to new revelations of the media, the objective of lafrappe was in reality, not to destroy the stolen truck, but was intended to eliminate two important Taliban leaders.
According to the investigation report of nato, 142 people were killed or injured in the us air strike which was launched at the request of the German Colonel Goerg klein, military commander of kunduz.
The greens, the SPD and the Left have asked Saturday Chancellor Angela Merkel (cdu), to decide as soon as possible before the federal parliament and to reveal what Guttenberg really knew about the incident.
Jürgen Trittin and his colleague from the Green Party, Renate Künast are of the opinion that Mrs Angela Merkel must clearly say if the strategy of targeted killing is part of the government's Afghan policy if the Chancery, the army and intelligence services have approved this new strategy.
The Government spokesman categorically rejects the criticism.
The chancellery has in any way influenced the interventions of the Army in Afghanistan, he said.
Saturday, there were increasingly high to express doutesquant the real reasons for the dismissal of the Inspector General Wolfgang Schneiderhan and the Secretary of State Peter Wichert, as presented by the department.
According to the information of the newspaper SPIEGEL, the information they had handed over to Guttenberg concerning the attack tankers were both correct and complete.
Officially, they would have concealed the existence of the report of NATO and some ministerial hidden embarrassing details.
In the entourage of two senior officials but it was suggested that they have informed the Ministry of Defence of the existence of several reports, including a two-page document of Colonel Klein and a report of the military police.
"the Frankfurter Allgemeiner Sonntagszeitung reported that Wichert would have meanwhile asked in a letter a clarification of the facts.
So far, it has not answered
Saturday, the department declined comment on these accusations and referred to the Committee of Inquiry of the federal parliament which would be the next Wednesday in order to bring light on the facts in question.
The worlds of fantasy
Some see awake, images and hear voices that nobody else sees or hears.
It is not only among mental patients, or under the influence of drugs, that the boundaries between fantasy and reality mingle.
As these phenomena occur during sleep, everything is going very well.
When we are lying in our rooms clouded, we can do without hindrance to the dreams and wildest fantasies.
However, awake, the experience of dream, hear and see things that others do not perceive, has the reputation in the Western world to be mad or drugged, or at least to be an original.
Such images and voices do not appear in the mental ill or under the influence of drugs.
It is our imagination that is in question: it is the same neural activity that allows us to design houses, paint pictures or write novels, but sometimes prompts the boundaries between the dream, madness and reality to melt.
A state of arousal aware, taking the form of a dream, can be in various forms, in the best case it is called visions, at worst madness.
But even if the trigger and the effect differ, visions of the mystical Hildegard von bingen, drug experiences of the Prophet of the New Age Carlos castaneda, the latter states of shamans, psychoses and hallucinations are attributable to very similar process.
There are hallucinations or delusions when the balance, substances neurotransmitter brain - first and foremost the dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and achétylcholine_OOV - breaks and that the interaction between the different parts of the brain is disrupted.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts occur very often during a schizophrenic psychosis.
The force of attraction land has more power on the person.
Since antiquity, philosophers and doctors have always looked at the relationship between the madness and the dream.
For aristotle, hallucinations were a form of rêve-éveillé_OOV; Wilhelm griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, found in 1861 "a great similarity between the madness and the dream," Sigmund Freud the dream was "a psychosis with all irregularities, imagination, delusions and illusions sensory who composed".
We are in autumn 2001 when Henning T turns into character in a comic book.
His body is in two dimensions to the colours.
The attraction has more power on him in the ceiling.
It is a blow.
Behind him creatures of devil ailées, grimaçantes, the mouth bloodied, showing its teeth.
They continue, give the shots feet with heavy boots, the cast against the walls, he feels pain throughout the body.
Thundering voice, nasty, howl, outgoing walls and radio.
It can no longer bear these voices who insult and humiliate.
Henning T. snatched two cables of its stereo, in fact a loop and attached to a hook attached to the ceiling.
He mounted on a baffle and goes on the loop around the neck.
It is obvious.
The loop stands out.
That you used a lesson, shout the voice in a chorus to extract the eardrum. 'care in a clinic and yourself! "
Today Henning T. has 40 years, he lived six acute psychosis, the last date of 2 years, the first in nearly 20 years.
It was triggered by LSD.
The diagnosis: psychosis schizo-affective, paranoid, it is, he takes medication for depression, mania and schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, he is married for three years.
During the psychosis I had terrible fears and deep despair.
The illusions are a cruel reality.
About one percent of the population suffers at least once in his life of schizophrenia; in psychiatric clinics is the most common illness after the depression.
In a crisis of schizophrenia, those concerned can no longer make the difference between the inside and the outside world, they find themselves in a state of hyper excitation, that they may suffer from hallucinations, megalomania, madness relational or persecution.
It is very common to hear the voice of votes, or dialogue.
The optical hallucinations are not rare.
The person concerned can no longer distinguish between the important and insignificant, the brain can no longer filter disturbing signals, the aware is drowned in the sensations.
Just as the dream, psychosis opens the locks to a tide of ideas and fantasies of deeper layers of conscience.
The perception of reality in psychosis is focused on the subject, according to Professor Thomas Fuchs, head of the department of Psychiatry at Heidelberg Chu (Allgemeine Psychiatry im Universitätsklinikum).
The schizophrenic is located in the centre of the situation, meaning focused on him.
At the same time it is found in a passive role, it is like a dream, overcome by events and cannot act on them actively.
That is why the schizophrenic often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
In general they do not have the opportunity to adjust the reality, the illusions are a cruel reality, wake up is excluded.
To experience once in her life of a hallucination.
Unlike the dream, according to Fuchs, the sensory structure and space to the reality that is seen during the psychosis, is fundamentally retained ".
The thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of lived in a real framework.
Why our brain such antics, is still a mystery to researchers.
Exceptional situations can bring everyone to momentarily lose the perception of reality, according to Fuchs.
But only a small number of people develop a psychosis.
There appears to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies on twins have shown that genes are not the only determinants.
The researchers speculate that the persons concerned are tiny brain.
It is assumed that the neural maturation of the brain is disrupted at an early stage of development for example by a viral infection of the mother during pregnancy, explained.
But what remains unexplained is how the neural system occurs and also the fact that it is not for many years.
Environmental factors also play a role - the stress or a traumatic experience can be a trigger of psychosis, if there is a predisposition.
Similarly the hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychosis because they act on neurotransmitters.
When our brains.
This is crazy, says professor of psychology Erich Kasten of Lübeck is that the psychotic suffer from their hallucinations and take medicines to undo while others buy drugs very expensive for atomic weapons.
The perception pleasant or unpleasant illusions is often just a matter of perspective.
Kasten brings together for ten years of reports on hallucinations and illusory image phenomena: last year he published his findings in a book entitled "The unreal world in our heads."
The hallucinations are phenomena typical psychoses but also an impressive number of many other diseases.
They include mental disorders such as borderline or depression but also the migraines, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, alzheimer ’ s disease or head trauma.
It is surprising that in certain conditions even the brains of healthy people is subject to hallucinations.
The hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of fragments of memories that normally are inhibited.
They take shape when the areas of the brain that address the sensory perception, are hyperactives or not sufficiently refrénées; when our brain heats but also when there is lack of stimulation.
The drugs can trigger this state as a brain injury or psychosis.
But also the lack of stimulus, stress, the sorrows of love or other mental states.
In recent studies, one third of participants acknowledges having made at least once in a lifetime experience of a hallucination.
In summer 2005 Sarah K. 16 years ago, she lives in a small town of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and it goes to high school.
A young girl to normal.
If there was not the images and voices.
During the recess, a young boy, thin, with long hair chestnut, send him the floor.
When she replied his comrades watch, surprised - nobody else sees or hears this boy.
They believe that this girl is a lunatic but Sarah K do not dream, it is certain.
She is awake, hear and see the boy as she sees and hears the girl who is seated beside her on the bench.
It can even see its presence temporarily.
It is a good feeling, she found that young sympathetic.
Am I crazy?, asks sometimes.
But she knows that this young and other visions are not real and they will disappear again.
The night appearances are, in general, frightening.
Often the visions are burdensome.
When it is in class, it is that it can follow the course because the professor is just present a new student in his eyes and ears when it is invisible to others and that the professor is clearly explaining equations in table.
The night appearances are, in general, frightening.
When, in the darkness of his bedroom, it expects sleep that came too little and too late, it often cannot make the distinction if she is awake or dream already, if the images she sees, faces grimaçants or the girl with bloody cuts on his arms and legs are before his eyes open or closed.
Let me quiet, cree to these creatures.
It does not speak or his parents or friends, they would for a mad.
Fall 2009. Sarah K. is now 20 years.
It was last year and she lives with her friend.
A year ago the hallucinations have ceased.
Since it came into contact by Internet with the psychologist Kasten she knows very well that it is not crazy.
The madness is also a work of art of despair.
When someone is socially isolated or not enough of stimulation, the probability is high that it has hallucinations after a certain time.
I assume that the brain is not busy enough, so there was.
Sarah K., only daughter, was afraid of the other children when she was small and often played alone.
Its hallucinations began when she learned to 13 years, the man she called dad, since it was in age to think, was not his real father.
This is the same brain areas that are active for visual hallucinations and acoustic, and for actual impressions and noise, so it is very difficult for people like Sarah K to the difference between the illusion and reality. "every experience," according to Kasten "in the brain, the reality is formed from there.
The hallucinations are also images that form in the brain, which is why they seem so real. "
For Kasten, nocturnal dreams are also a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people do not differ fundamentally from those in acute psychosis.
Unlike the schizophrenic, mentally healthy person is able to recognize that the fantasies are not real images.
That is why Kasten advises his patients to cherish the hallucinations as a particular talent.
There is a step between the dream and the hallucination.
In our world too focused on the conscience has unfortunately quickly tend to take the imaginary experiences for ailments, according to Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and doctor, head of clinical psychiatry and psychotherapy Hospital Florence Nightingale in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious disease, painful but which also contains something positive, creator - madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-degenhard has studied the form of so-called oniroïde experience, a particular form of the amendment to the conscience being stirred by the dream.
The experienced oniroïdes are very complex semi-rêves which are perceived as real by the lives and that it cannot differentiate the dream even when it is in a state of arousal.
The state of consciousness Oniroïde occurs during a trauma or in situations of extreme pathologies as for patients with Polyradiculopathie which fully aware, experience a paralysis engine.
According to Schmidt-Degenhard, when a human being is threatened by a loss of itself and the world, due to a comprehensive and lasting inability to move, it replaces the real situation that affects his life, by his own imaginary world that is divorced from reality.
It is a state of mental boundary between the dream and the hallucination.
As it is not possible to overcome the situation in reality, a change of world but the real situation is represented in the imagination.
It is, in fact, a form of intensive methods and interpretation, in a situation intolerable in itself, an organization that is given to us men, not to sink into none of the loss of consciousness.
Everything is real even later in the memories.
The Zurichois Peter Cornelius Classen, art historian also describes his experiences oniroïdes in his book "Change of Heart" as action to safeguard the soul.
He was 49 years, when his hand for a trip of several days after the operation of a heart valve followed a transplant; during this time, his body is condemned to remain in intensive care.
Claussen plunges into a world that it has created, visit the places foreign trip in time. It is as old man bed in a sanatorium rail, a robot in his mind on his health care.
He lives in the Middle Ages among nobles who manufacture drugs based on blood.
It is abducted by a Greek to who takes in his country, he is riding with his hospital bed in the Alps and meeting a Korean Mafia.
It absorbs completely in this imaginary world, everything is real even later in his memories.
According to Claussen these domestic travel are fundamentally different from any dream.
The dream is a completely different state, wrote in describing what he lived.
Instead of dreams, memories from travel disorders are extremely clear and very detailed even years later.
We can even say that they are much more distinct and more intensive than the real experience.
The intensity of this had been slapped the horizon of our other everyday experiences, according to the psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, the oniroïdes mania, psychosis, hallucinations and psychedelic experience shows how our internal representations of the external reality are fragile even in a state of intelligence.
Any change in the state of consciousness, summarizes the psychologist Kasten "may cause a distortion of what we call reality."
An experience that can be very rewarding.
