Acciona dispute its first motorway in Australia to Hochtief and Bouygues
Acciona is fighting for its first motorway concession in australia, on which it is already working as a business manager of energy and water.
The site at stake is a tunnel estimated at 700 million Australian dollars (about 1 047 million euros).
The French company Bouygues and the German company Hochtief are its rivals.
A tunnel of 5 kilometres long in the Australian city of brisbane, on the east coast, such is the option to allow Acciona to settle in the country as a company of public works and highways dealer.
The mayor of the city wants to have by the end of 2014.
After choosing the public / private partnership (PPP for its initials in English) to complete the project, as part of a business plan under the tutelage of SRS & Young, the local administration already has a list of finalists who will be responsible for the construction and operation of the toll.
Pending the submission of their bids in May next year, the planned investment amounts to 1 700 million Australian dollars (about 1 million euros) and in the last phase three consortia, with a significant presence of European manufacturers.
The group called Transcity is led by Acciona, only Spanish company in smooth, and his associates are MDBs and Ghella.
The first is one of the largest manufacturers, while the second, located in Italy, is one of the largest European specialists to work underground.
Against the team of Acciona, shoe the consortium Northern Direct, with the presence of the British company Laing O'Rourke, manager of the Australian infrastructure Transfield and of the French manufacturer Bouygues.
The third and final consortium that has passed the test is LBRJV, whose capital is divided between the Australian Leighton (a subsidiary of the German manufacturer Hochtief, which states in its turn to the participation of ACS), another local company, Baulderstone (owned by the German group Bilfinger Berger) and the Welsh company specializing in public works, Razel.
The Australian market infrastructure promises of major projects and privatisation, but there is a great difficulty, if not through the acquisition of a local construction company.
A strategy that followed the companies Hochtief and Bilfinger, already mentioned, in addition to their Asian references, and which is still a step not validated for the Spanish giants of the sector.
ACS was just to win a place on the market by his participation of 30% in Hochtief, owner of Leighton.
Active millionaires
Acciona on a geographical area of the utmost importance for the sector, on which it already has a large presence through its energy supplier and activity in the sector desalination.
Among other assets, it has the largest wind park, one of Waubra (192 MW) in Victoria, and the consolidation of companies responsible for building and managing the Dessalinisateur of Adelaide, with a budget of $700 million.
It now intends to consolidate these two areas and take advantage of synergies to enter the markets of the construction and management of infrastructure.
The road toll underground, promoted by the Office of the infrastructure of the city of Brisbane and the Northern Link (north), is called upon to Link the motorway west of Toowong peripheral to Kelvin Grove (see map), by 4 kilometres of tunnel. It is the largest project to reduce traffic congestion in Brisbane.
The timetable set by the administration indicates that the auction will take place during the summer of 2010 and that the work will begin in December next year.
Despite the fact that the toll will be open to traffic at the end of 2014, it is not anticipated that the site is completed before 2016.
The tunnel has begun to be designed in 2005.
It will include two times two lanes, an electronic toll system and a complex ventilation system.
The Queensland government will provide 500 million Australian dollars (308 million euros) for its funding.
